text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild]]%0a%0a!Steven Crowder Discriminating against AAVE%0a%0a:Author: JacobF%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aSteven Crowder adopts a stereotypical AAVE accent to discriminate against AAVE speakers%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aContent warning: the following article and link contain references to multiple racist stereotypes and caricatures of African-Americans%0a%0aIn the following link, right-wing political commentator Steven Crowder is reacting to a video detailing a bill passed by the Biden administration which allocates $5.2 billion dollars to farmers of color. %0a%0ahttps://twitter.com/JasonSCampbell/status/1371856007203336194%0a%0aCrowder feels, for a variety of ignorant and ill-formed reasons, that the bill is ridiculous, and in place of attempting any sort of real analytical rebuttal, instead adopts a stereotypical AAVE accent and begins a bizarre 'impression' of what he imagines a farmer of color to be. Elements of his own impersonation he seems to place particular emphasis on are his renderings of dental fricatives as alveolar plosives, i.e. th-stopping (ex pronouncing 'that' as [dæt]), and his final consonant deletion (ex pronouncing 'motherfucker' as [məðɐfəkɐ]), both of which are features in AAVE accents.%0a%0a%0aThough he does not explicitly reference his own impersonation as being ungrammatical, it is clear through both his frequent use of racist stereotypes of African-Americans (he and his friends mention trying to plant a 'Hennessy Tree' and an issue with dirt being rendered infertile due to 'a high level of meth') and his overall opinion that the bill is a bad idea, that he is coding this speech as ungrammatical and 'evidence' of low intelligence. Crowder intends for his viewers to see his impression and grammar as 'clear proof' that farmers of color do not know how to farm, and that any money given to them would be wasted.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210425-022726-592130#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Usage of “fixin’ to” in Texas %0a-> - albert_l%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0ahttps://www.texasstandard.org/stories/the-case-for-fixin-to-as-the-official-verb-of-texas/%0a%0aI found an interesting story in the Texas Standard, where W.F. Strong, a Fullbright scholar and professor of Culture and Communication at the University of Texas Rio Grande Valley, provides his personal experience with the verb “fixin’ to” as a native resident of Texas, and offers an interesting grammatical perspective on the usage of the verb.%0a%0aOne aspect of the verb “fixin’ to” that W.F. Strong highlights is the malleability of the verb, as well as its ability to be used in various situations. He defines these as “Intentionality”, “Contemplation”, and “Forewarning”, and provides a comedic example of the verb used multiple times in the same sentence: “I was fixin’ to fix it this mornin’, but I decided to fix breakfast first cuz I saw all these fixins which I knew would make a fine omelette. So right now I’m fixin’ to eat, but when I finish I’m fixin to look for my tools –if I can find ‘em – and get started on fixin’ your mower.” W.F. Strong also provides an interesting regional variation of “fixin’ to”, where the final “o” is replaced with “a” leaving the meaning unchanged. %0a%0aI think it is interesting to note that not only are certain phrases and words regionally diverse across the language speaking population, but also contain regional variations in usage and expression which improve upon its diversity. %0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210425-022726-592130#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: A:)%0a(:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild:)
